Final Project

By Sanaz Ebrahimi

Introduction

The purpose of this project is to take raw data from the UCSB menâ€™s soccer team and find a model that will best predict a playerâ€™s total impact.

What Technology gives us this data?

Many of UCSBâ€™s athletics teams have shifted over to using tracking products from the brand spt so that they can track athletic performance. The UCSB menâ€™s soccer team wears these trackers everyday to practice and during games in order to elevate performance and avoid injury after the data is interpreted. How it works is that each player shows up to practice with a sports bra on which they will then hold their tracker. They are handed their track before every event and then they turn it off when the practice or game is over. The tracker collects all personal metrics for each player and this can later be used to analyze changes in performance and health.

Informational video : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=daPCQhMG7BU&t=32s

Why might these model be useful?

Many of the predictors in this project are dependent on running speeds and how that carries onto total impact on the body. The main reason this model would be helpful to the teams understanding is to see how players that do not run as much are doing in terms of total impact. If their total impact to their body is low but they are still playing well we can cross-reference this with the game day statistics to evaluate the trade offs between exerted body effort or placement/technique on the field.

Loading the Data

This data was sent to me from a staff member from the UCSB menâ€™s soccer team because I work with them. Most of it was already cleaned and therefore made it easier to look through. The codebook for this project is in my zipped files and shows the specfics for each predictor.

The first step here is opening the data set and then using the function clean_names(). Again to deal with the replicate rows that account for each games 1st half, 2nd half and full game we want to filter our data to only include events with segment name â€œ*â€ because this column includes â€œ1st Halfâ€ and â€œ2nd Halfâ€. By getting rid of the first and second half we successfully keep the full game data points in our data set. Next we want to take out all the columns starting with â€œhrâ€ because they are all empty and this way our data will look more concise(same with â€œevent_tagsâ€). Lastly we must take out rows â€œimpact_lightâ€, â€œimpact_heavyâ€, and â€œimpact_mediumâ€ because the sum of these three columns adds up to our outcome. We do not want this in our data set because it would make the data colinear and ruin the predictions we are trying to get by fitting the models later. The total_distance_m also has to be taken out because it is just the sum of walk_distance_m, jog_distance_m, run_distance_m, and sprint_distance_m and we would rather see the impact of each running speed instead of just the total.

Data Splitting

set.seed(5555) #so that the same random variables are used when we re run the code 

msocf22_split <- initial_split(msocf22, prop = 0.70,
                               strata = total_impact) #stratifying on the outcome variable 
msocf22_train <- training(msocf22_split)
msocf22_test <- testing(msocf22_split)

dim(msocf22_train)/nrow(msocf22) #checking if the proportions of the split data are correct 
## [1] 0.69863946 0.01972789
dim(msocf22_test)/nrow(msocf22)
## [1] 0.30136054 0.01972789

We want to split our data into a testing and training data set stratifying on the outcome.This is because our outcomes distribution was heavily skewed. We stratify on outcome because we would like to maintain the distribution of the outcome for all the resampling. In the first line of code in this block we set.seed() so that the same random variables are used every time we rerun the code.

Exploratory Data Analysis

We choose to do all the exploratory data analysis( eda ) on the testing data because that is what we are fitting all the models to. We would like to see how this data is acting so that we can better understand how to deal with it before and after we analysis the models.

library(corrplot)

msocf22_train %>%
  select_if(is.numeric) %>% 
  cor() %>% 
  corrplot(type = "lower")

Here we construct a correlation plot with all the possible relevant predictors so far to see if anything stands out and if we should be cautious of that. The first thing that should catch your eyes is that â€œjog_distance_mâ€ and â€œzone_2_distance_mâ€ have a perfect positive correlation and so does â€œwalk_distance_mâ€ and â€œzone_distance_1â€. This can be explained by the fact that these zone speeds are the exact same speeds needed for a player to fall into either the jog, walk, run, or sprint categories. This is helpful to us because we can determine that our recipe does not need each zone distance because that speed is already accounted for within â€œjog_distance_mâ€, â€œrun_distance_mâ€, â€œsprint_distance_mâ€, and â€œwalk_distance_mâ€. However, this also opens the possibility to creating interactions between the predictors to again create a more condense model and not waste time looking at a predictor that is already within another one of our predictors. Lastly one should note that we only have positive correlations because every predictor we are looking at has to do with running, speed and efforts put in. Generally the more effort you put in the faster you go explaining most of the positive correlations we are witnessing here. There is no pair of predictors here where doing worse for one will be better for the other. To combat the perfect correlation values we talked about before we learned in lecture that we can use the principal component analysis (a form of dimension reduction) and take the relationships we deem as â€œinterestingâ€ and condense them into less predictors. This way we save all the data and simply the recipe we will create later.

msocf22_train %>%
  ggplot(aes(performance_duration_min, total_impact))+ #wish to see the relationship between performance minutes and outcome based on athlete
  geom_point(alpha=0.1) +

  facet_wrap(~player_name,scales="free")+ # i'd like a plot per player so we put "~" player to get all the players

  )

Here we are creating a visual of each athletesâ€™ minutes played versus total_impact. These visuals are easier to create for the regression problems because we can take a qualitative column (athletes) and simply plot multiple relationships on the same visual. This part of EDA showed us that Athlete 7 has lots of missing data so we should not really take them into account. This is why exploratory data analysis is helpful because we do not have to scrummage through all the data to identity missing data. The reason I wanted to see this plot is mainly because these two predictors had a surprisingly low correlation value of .23 when I expected them not to. This way we can see in detail what typically happens when each player plays for longer. A lot of the plots show that each athletes peak impact value is roughly around 50 minutes. This to me means that when a player is put into a game they are able to perform best and at their maximum ability if they are not forced to play the entire 90 minute game. The same goes for practice duration.

After the last plot we saw that Athlete 7 does not have many data points indicating they left the team or were injured, so their data is not necessarily useful to us.

ggplot(msocf22_train, aes(x=walk_distance_m, y=total_impact, fill=event_type)) +
  geom_boxplot() # here we construct a normal boxplot with ggplot

The relationship between this bar plot was mainly to see if players are using training as more of a time to heal and relax their bodies keeping it low impact or not. The plots have similar mean values because a training session is much longer than a game meaning even if they are not doing as much they have time to walk around as much as they would in a game. However one can see that the walk distance for games is much lower than ones from training because in training some players who are subbed off can walk around much more than they would in a game. The outliers we see on the game box plot could be the defenders on our team because they do have time to walk around more when we are on the attack side and they still have high impact values because when they do play they are exerting a lot of physical energy.

ggplot(msocf22_train, aes(x=intensity, y=total_impact, fill=event_type)) +
  geom_boxplot() # here we construct a normal boxplot with ggplot

This plot I created after running the random forest model because through one of our visuals it showed us that intensity was the most relevant predictor. It is smart to check out the relationship between them to see if anything stands out. It seems that intensity is much higher on game days which makes a lot of sense because most players are running the whole 90 minutes. The larger range on the game box plot could also be explained by how much playing time a player is getting and how much intensity they are putting in affecting the total impact and the distribution we see. The training box plot also makes sense because there shouldnâ€™t be a huge range when everyone is exerting the same amount of effort for practice when the coach is allowed to stop them and talk to them etc. The outliers can be explained by how sometimes players who played the entire game the day before are able to sit out for training to relax their bodies meaning other players are exerting much more effort then them making them have a higher total impact throughout training.

This histogram of our outcome is uni-model and right-sckew. The distribution makes sense because total impact is dependent on how much players are on the field and how hard they choose to go. Our trackerâ€™s metrics make it normal to have a lower total_impact because anything too high would mean the player is going out of their comfort zone/ are not accumulated to the workout probably leaving them sore the next day. This is not what we want in order to prevent injury, that is why it is important for us to track things like this to make sure players have a steady and healthy increase of action during games and practices. The last thing we should note is that there is a positive skew on our distribution here.

Model Building

msocf22_recipe <- recipe(total_impact ~ performance_duration_min + walk_distance_m + jog_distance_m+ 
                           run_distance_m + sprint_distance_m + sprint_efforts + hard_running_m +  work_rate_m_min + top_speed_m_s + intensity + zone_1_distance_m + zone_2_distance_m + zone_3_distance_m + zone_4_distance_m + zone_5_distance_m + zone_6_distance_m + zone_7_distance_m + zone_8_distance_m, data = msocf22_train) %>%
  step_normalize(all_predictors())%>% #normalize the model, same as step center and step scale
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
 step_pca(walk_distance_m,zone_1_distance_m,jog_distance_m,zone_2_distance_m,run_distance_m,zone_3_distance_m,zone_4_distance_m,sprint_distance_m,zone_7_distance_m,num_comp = 4) #due to the high correlations we use pca with 4 components to simply the recipe but keep all data in tact

Our recipe is a very important part of building our models. Now that we saw what data to get rid of and alter in our data cleaning and eda and wer proceed by creating the backbone of our models. Initially in our recipe we choose to get rid of zone distances for all 8 zones because they were just a reiteration of the speeds contained in either walking, running, sprinting, or jogging distances. However, in order to yield better results and not get rid of predictors we problem solved by using the PCA method. In this method we were able to combine,walk_distance_m and zone_1_distance_m,jog_distance_m and zone_2_distance_m, run_distance_m and zone_3_distance_m as well as zone_4_distance_m, and finally sprint_distance_m and zone_7_distance_m. To combat all the pairs and the one trios we used num_comp as four because we went from 9 predictors to basically four. We choose to have 4 componenets instead of one because we would like to see how each type of movement: running, jogging, walking, and sprinting affect the outcome. This is because our whole project is based on different types of running and speeds and how they impact the body. Lastly because we know the data set and we know predictors like the load zones are irrelevant to the outcome factor we may simply remove them.

We learned that for most machine learning problems in this course it is safe to use 5 or 10 folds when performing cross fold validation. With k fold cross validation we avoid using the whole data set instead we have k-1 folds that we fit with our training data to learn the data and then finally we can apply the learned models to our 1 fold of testing data.

General Understanding

We choose to test many models on this data including a linear regression, polynomial regression, ridge, lasso, k nearest neighbors, random forest, and boosted trees. For the most part the understanding for models here is to note we have regression model because even though our outcome is categorical we consider there to be too high a range for our numerical values that have categorical meanings. We will basically put our values into bins that we can deal with after the fact. To start making our models we always want to use the set_engine() function with the specific model we are using and then from there we create a workflow that will take in our initial recipe and our new model and put them together so that we can then fit the model. For most of our models you will notice we have the auto_plot() function to look at a visual and then we will use the select_best() function to get the best metric for all the models at the end. Another thing to note is that we will fit all of our mdoels on the training data so that the models can learn and then eventually once we have the best model we will fit it to out testing data. Lastly we will tune all these models so that we can incorporate our folds we created earlier and yield the best results by learning on the training data.

Since this is the first time we are running a model more complex and similar to the others there are some new things in the code. First we now are tuning this model so that we can get an idea of what is the ideal polynomial degree for our polynomial regression model. In this step we fit a polynomial regression with our degree range going from 1-4. After the model was fit we used the function auto_plot() on our tuned model to see how it would do in terms of the polynomial degree in comparison to both rmse and rsq.This is the part where we can identify the best degree. From both of the visuals it is easy to see that the model has a higher rsq and lower rmse at lower polynomial degrees. This is ideal because a high rsq shows that most of the variability caused in the outcome is explained by our predictors and a low rmse means we have a low error rate. Secondly we then move on by selecting the best rmse value because that is what we will be using to compare all the models later. We finalize a new workflow with this best value so that we can fit the model with it and then extract the best rmse and even fit the testing data to see how it does. In this case we were interested so we can see that that training versus testing rmse almost doubles which is not ideal.

The same work goes into our code here as before, we tune our model and then proceed to find the best values from the training data. The ridge model is unlike the lasso model in which it only shrinks predictors instead of making their value basically zero. The lasso model will shrink and eliminate preidctors to a zero value faster if they are irrelevant. As we can see in the visual the rmse becomes larger as lambda becomes larger which is not what we want, we prefer a smaller root mean square error. However, the r^2 value which we talked about earlier gets larger as lambda gets around 1e+00 and then gets much lower when it nears 1e+03. This means there is an ideal value of lambda where around 1e+00 where both r^2 and root mean square error hold ideal values. Another thing to note is that we looked at the testng data here again and the training to testing rmse is still almost doubled. Again, this is not ideal we would want the values to be as close as possible to each other because our training data is used to learned the behavior our data and our testing data is saved to see if the models are valid. A problem that usually creates a difference between the training and testing data results is over fitting. This could also be our problem.

Conclusion:

Through all the data analysis and changes that were made to this project we ended up seeing that the ridge and lasso models were the most compatible with our goal of using the predictors in our recipe to predict the total impact each athlete was enduring. Due to the complex models we were using we may notice that the increase in our rmse from training to testing data does indicate over fitting in our process. In a complex parametric model adding more parameters can add flexibility which is positive but it may also cause over fitting which is not good. Over fitting is explained by the fact that the model has trouble generalizing the data and is so adapted to the training data that it makes inaccurate conclusions. Some causes for over fitting may be that our training data may have still had irrelevant information that would be considered noise. This noise or irrelevant information would confuse our model leading it to give us inaccurate conclusion. Secondly if our model had been training too long with our training data that wasnâ€™t really that large it could have easily adapted to it and not been able to make distinguish differences that are important anymore. Lastly, due to some of our models being super complex like the random forest and boosted tree the model could have had enough time to learn what kind of noise was in the training data. The problem becomes that as our model has adapted to the noise in the training data set once it is used on the testing data set it cannot detect the new noise as well and will give us inaccurate predictions. This could be a reason for why our data did not do as well on the random forest and boosted trees when most models usually do. The second thing to takeaway is that due to our lasso regression model excelling we could see that maybe we had too many predictors. In the lecture about regularization we were taught that the lasso regression model operates with variable selection which means some predictorsâ€™ estimates can be shrunk down to zero and basically eliminated. This is telling that maybe as mentioned before we had too many parameters and that is why we were over fitting and also why our lasso regression model was the best. To combat some of these problems in the near future I would take some time to run more eda and look deeper into our predictor relationships. There could be more changes that need to happen to our recipe. Although I am glad I did not rerun the random forest because the over fitting in this model wouldâ€™ve meant the complexity of the random forest would have been too much to yield good results anyways.
